# Focus — Explanation Voice (Juniors First)

Inline explainers ship through the **Focus extension + Python backend**, not Cursor rules.
VS Code and Cursor users both see the same HUD JSON. Claude Code / Codex are out of scope
for this extension UX.

## Runtime (product)

Acronym teaching lives in `expand_acronyms_for_juniors()` in `src/focus/hud/explain.py`.
Any summary / detail / explanation string goes through that helper before it reaches the IDE.
Add new product terms there — do not rely on `.cursor/rules` for end-user copy.

## Expand acronyms on first use

Write bare acronyms in generators when natural (`AST`, `BFS`); the helper expands the first
occurrence to **`ACRONYM (Full Name)`**. Skip if already expanded.

| Bad | Good |
|---|---|
| Sets `kind="function"` on the Definition record being built. | Records this as a function in the AST. |
| (generator output) Records this as a function in the AST. | (end user sees) Records this as a function in the AST (Abstract Syntax Tree). |

## Prefer intent over machinery

Explain **what this change does for the reader**, not what the syntax does.

## Do not repeat the enclosing function name

The Focus header above `def` already names the symbol. Inline 💡 detail should name
**what’s in the hunk** (variable, kind, call), not restating `_extract_definitions`.

## Litmus test

Read the 💡 line out loud. If *you* pause to ask “what does that mean?”, rewrite it.
